### Description

I've been using the following logging config to work with logDNA (I stripped out the other handlers):

```
LOGGING_CONFIG = {
    'handlers': {
        'logDNA': {
            'level': 'DEBUG',
            'class': 'logging.handlers.LogDNAHandler',
            'key': os.environ['LOG_LOGDNA_KEY'],
            'options': {
                'app': f'auto_pitch_lib',
                'env': os.environ["ENVIRONMENT_NAME"],
                'index_meta': True
            }
        }
    },
    'root': {
        'level': 'DEBUG',
        'handlers': ['console', 'file', 'logDNA']
    }
}
```

## Problem

What I noticed is the `env` isn't set anywhere when searching through app logs in the LogDNA webapp.
The webapp doesn't seem to have any notion of environment, so my solution is to set the `ENVIRONMENT_NAME` in the app name.

```
LOGGING_CONFIG = {
    'handlers': {
        'logDNA': {
            'level': 'DEBUG',
            'class': 'logging.handlers.LogDNAHandler',
            'key': os.environ['LOG_LOGDNA_KEY'],
            'options': {
                'app': f'auto_pitch_lib-{os.environ["ENVIRONMENT_NAME"]}',
                'index_meta': True
            }
        }
    },
    'root': {
        'level': 'DEBUG',
        'handlers': ['console', 'file', 'logDNA']
    }
}
```

Is the `env` option legacy that needs to be removed? If so I think the readme should be updated. 
If the `env` is actually being used I'd like to know how to use it properly.

Thanks
